    "body" : "<p>There are other ways we can use JAVA 11 for 32-bit OS, there are some 3rd party website which has been confirmed by JAVA community provides JAVA 11 for 32-bit</p>\n<p>As an example Amazon Corretto. Follow the below link for more details</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/corretto/latest/corretto-11-ug/downloads-list.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://docs.aws.amazon.com/corretto/latest/corretto-11-ug/downloads-list.html</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 935202,
      "reputation" : 50314,
      "user_id" : 964243,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 66,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/fL1rH.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Boann",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/964243/boann"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1760392125,
    "last_edit_date" : 1760392125,
    "creation_date" : 1730143445,
    "answer_id" : 79134843,
    "question_id" : 70225754,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The very nice &quot;<a href=\"https://adoptium.net/temurin/releases/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Eclipse Temurin by Adoptium</a>&quot; project still provides 32-bit Windows builds of the JRE and JDK for up-to and including <strong>Java 19</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Officially this requires at least Windows 10</strong>, so there might be rough edges, but personally I've found it installs without complaint on 32-bit Windows 7 and it works fine so far as I can tell.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>Edit: A company called Bellsoft, an OpenJDK contributor, produces ready-to-download builds of OpenJDK <strong>8, 11, 17, and 21</strong> for systems explicitly including <strong>Windows 7 SP1 32-bit</strong>. See: <a href=\"https://bell-sw.com/pages/supported-configurations/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://bell-sw.com/pages/supported-configurations/</a>. I tried the 32-bit Java 21 on Windows 7 and it works fine.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>Note that <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/479\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JEP 479</a>, delivered in Java 24, removes the 32-bit Windows code entirely from the OpenJDK source. Similarly, <a href=\"https://openjdk.org/jeps/503\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">JEP 503</a>, delivered in Java 25, removes x86 32-bit code for <em>all</em> operating systems. It's possible a third-party could choose to merge the code back and support it on their own terms, but not likely. x86 has almost totally moved to 64-bit, and the people who haven't are probably content with old Java anyway.</p>\n"
  } ],
