  "body" : "<p>I wanted to install Java 11 on my Windows 32-bit System.</p>\n<p>I've searched <a href=\"https://www.oracle.com/in/java/technologies/javase/jdk11-archive-downloads.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this Official Java 11 Download Page</a> doesn't contain any download for a 32-bit system.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/uBl4c.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/uBl4c.png\" alt=\"![image|690x451](upload://eydqHMGEHusQpITxQz268orsb7p.png)\" /></a></p>\n<p>But still I didn't lose my hope, I saw <a href=\"https://adoptium.net/releases.html?variant=openjdk11\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this site</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/S5Cic.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/S5Cic.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\" /></a></p>\n<p>But when I saw the <code>2012r2</code>, I think it won't work for my <strong>2009</strong> Windows 7 32-it system, but anyways its a different version than Java Official one.</p>\n<p>I even saw <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/46356345/can-java-9-run-on-a-32-bit-os/46510935#46510935\">this page</a></p>\n<p>It is about Java 9 but even though I don't think the command (which is in the 1st post) doesn't work (I haven't tested it yet).</p>\n"
